{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20822"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97042"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79658"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12470"},{"type":"tags","id":"12655"},{"type":"tags","id":"12656"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32986"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97042"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following stains is most useful for identifying amoebae in tissue specimens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giemsa stain","Silver stain","Acid-fast stain","Mucicarmine stain","Periodic acid-Schiff stain"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EPeriodic acid-Schiff stain\u003C/strong\u003E is the most useful stain for identifying amoebae in tissue specimens. This stain highlights the glycogen-rich cytoplasm of amoebae, causing them to appear magenta. The PAS stain oxidises the glycogen in the amoebic cytoplasm, creating aldehydes that react with Schiff reagent to produce the characteristic magenta colour. This makes amoebae readily visible against the background tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiemsa stain\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to identify blood parasites such as \u003Cem\u003EPlasmodium\u003C/em\u003E species (malaria), \u003Cem\u003EBabesia\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ETrypanosoma\u003C/em\u003E. It stains nuclear material but is not the preferred method for tissue amoebae.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilver stain\u003C/strong\u003E (such as Grocott-Gomori methenamine silver) is typically used to identify fungi like \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii\u003C/em\u003E, as well as some bacteria like \u003Cem\u003ELegionella\u003C/em\u003E species. It has limited utility for amoeba identification.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcid-fast stain\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to identify mycobacteria such as \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium leprae\u003C/em\u003E, as well as some \u003Cem\u003ENocardia\u003C/em\u003E species. It relies on the acid-fast property of mycobacterial cell walls and is not useful for amoebae.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucicarmine stain\u003C/strong\u003E is used primarily to identify mucin-producing organisms like \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/em\u003E and adenocarcinomas. It is not effective for amoebae.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon pathogenic amoebae that might be identified using PAS stain include \u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ENaegleria fowleri\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EAcanthamoeba\u003C/em\u003E species, and \u003Cem\u003EBalamuthia mandrillaris\u003C/em\u003E. The PAS stain is particularly valuable in diagnosing amoebic infections of the central nervous system, such as granulomatous amoebic encephalitis or primary amoebic meningoencephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Periodic acid-Schiff (PAS) stain is the preferred method for identifying amoebae in tissue specimens due to their glycogen-rich cytoplasm.","Amoebae contain glycogen-rich cytoplasm that stains magenta with PAS stain, making them visible against background tissue.","Other histological stains like acid-fast, silver, mucicarmine, and Giemsa have specific applications for different microorganisms but limited utility for amoeba identification."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 402."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79658"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79658"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:44:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:45:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97042"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"